# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ethereum
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ethereum/developers-accounts] An Ethereum account is an entity with an ether (ETH) balance that can send messages on Ethereum.
[src:ethereum/developers-accounts] Accounts can be user-controlled or deployed as smart contracts.
[src:ethereum/developers-accounts] To help you better understand this page, we recommend you first read through our introduction to Ethereum.
[src:ethereum/developers-accounts] An account is made up of a pair of cryptographic keys: public and private.
[src:ethereum/developers-accounts] They help prove that a transaction was actually signed by the sender and prevent forgeries.
[src:ethereum/developers-accounts] Your private key is what you use to sign transactions, so it grants you custody over the funds associated with your account.
[src:ethereum/developers-accounts] You never really hold cryptocurrency, you hold private keys – the funds are always on Ethereum's ledger.
[src:ethereum/developers-accounts] This prevents malicious actors from broadcasting fake transactions because you can always verify the sender of a transaction.
[src:ethereum/developers-accounts] If Alice wants to send ether from her own account to Bob’s account, Alice needs to create a transaction request and send it out to the network for verification.
[src:ethereum/developers-accounts] Ethereum’s usage of public-key cryptography ensures that Alice can prove that she originally initiated the transaction request.
[src:ethereum/developers-accounts] Without cryptographic mechanisms, a malicious adversary Eve could simply publicly broadcast a request that looks something like “send 5 ETH from Alice’s account to Eve’s account,” and no one would be able to verify that it didn’t come from Alice.
[src:ethereum/developers-accounts] When you want to create an account, most libraries will generate you a random private key.
[src:ethereum/developers-accounts] A private key is made up of 64 hex characters and can be encrypted with a password.
[src:ethereum/developers-accounts] The public key is generated from the private key using the Elliptic Curve Digital Signature Algorithm (opens in a new tab).
[src:ethereum/developers-accounts] You get a public address for your account by taking the last 20 bytes of the Keccak-256 hash of the public key and adding `0x` to the beginning.
[src:ethereum/developers-accounts] This means an Externally owned account (EOA) has a 42-character address (20-byte segment which is 40 hexadecimal characters plus the `0x` prefix).
[src:ethereum/developers-accounts] The following example shows how to use a signing tool called Clef (opens in a new tab) to generate a new account.
[src:ethereum/developers-accounts] Clef is an account management and signing tool that comes bundled with the Ethereum client, Geth (opens in a new tab).
[src:ethereum/developers-accounts] The `clef newaccount` command creates a new key pair and saves them in an encrypted keystore.
[src:ethereum/developers-accounts] It is possible to derive new public keys from your private key, but you cannot derive a private key from public keys.
[src:ethereum/developers-accounts] It is vital to keep your private keys safe and, as the name suggests, **PRIVATE**.
[src:ethereum/developers-accounts] You need a private key to sign messages and transactions which output a signature.
[src:ethereum/developers-accounts] Others can then take the signature to derive your public key, proving the author of the message.
[src:ethereum/developers-accounts] In your application, you can use a JavaScript library to send transactions to the network.
[src:ethereum/developers-accounts] The contract address is usually given when a contract is deployed to the Ethereum Blockchain.
[src:ethereum/developers-accounts] The address comes from the creator's address and the number of transactions sent from that address (the “nonce”).
[src:ethereum/developers-accounts] There is also another type of key in Ethereum, introduced when Ethereum switched from proof-of-work to proof-of-stake based consensus.
[src:ethereum/developers-accounts] These are 'BLS' keys and they are used to identify validators.
[src:ethereum/developers-accounts] These keys can be efficiently aggregated to reduce the bandwidth required for the network to come to consensus.
[src:ethereum/developers-accounts] Without this key aggregation the minimum stake for a validator would be much higher.
[src:ethereum/developers-accounts] A wallet is an interface or application that lets you interact with your Ethereum account, either an externally-owned account or a contract account.
[src:ethereum/developers-accounts] Watch Austin walk you through hash functions, and key pairs.
[src:ethereum/developers-dapps] A decentralized application (dapp) is an application built on a decentralized network that combines a smart contract and a frontend user interface.
[src:ethereum/developers-dapps] On Ethereum, smart contracts are accessible and transparent – like open APIs – so your dapp can even include a smart contract that someone else has written.
[src:ethereum/developers-dapps] Before learning about dapps, you should cover the blockchain basics and read about the Ethereum network and how it's decentralized.
[src:ethereum/developers-dapps] A dapp has its backend code running on a decentralized peer-to-peer network.
[src:ethereum/developers-dapps] Contrast this with an app where the backend code is running on centralized servers.
[src:ethereum/developers-dapps] A dapp can have frontend code and user interfaces written in any language (just like an app) to make calls to its backend.
[src:ethereum/developers-dapps] Furthermore, its frontend can get hosted on decentralized storage such as IPFS (opens in a new tab).
[src:ethereum/developers-dapps] To introduce dapps, we need to introduce smart contracts – a dapp's backend for lack of a better term.
[src:ethereum/developers-dapps] For a detailed overview, head to our section on smart contracts.
[src:ethereum/developers-dapps] A smart contract is code that lives on the Ethereum blockchain and runs exactly as programmed.
[src:ethereum/developers-dapps] Once smart contracts are deployed on the network you can't change them.
[src:ethereum/developers-dapps] Dapps can be decentralized because they are controlled by the logic written into the contract, not an individual or company.
[src:ethereum/developers-dapps] This also means you need to design your contracts very carefully and test them thoroughly.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] Ethereum Classic maintains the original, unaltered history of the Ethereum network.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] The Ethereum project's mainnet was initially released via Frontier on 30 July 2015.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] However, due to a hack of a third-party project, The DAO, the Ethereum Foundation created a new version of the Ethereum mainnet on 20 July 2016 with an irregular state change implemented that erased the DAO theft from the Ethereum blockchain history.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] The Ethereum Foundation applied their trademark to the new, altered version of the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] The older, unaltered version of Ethereum was renamed and continued on as Ethereum Classic.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] Ethereum Classic's native Ether token is a cryptocurrency traded on digital currency exchanges under the currency code ETC.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] Ether is created as a reward to network nodes for a process known as "mining", which validates computations performed on Ethereum Classic's EVM.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] Several codenamed prototypes of the Ethereum platform were developed by the Ethereum Foundation, as part of their proof-of-concept series, prior to the official launch of the Frontier network.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] Ethereum Classic followed this codebase after the DAO incident.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] On 28 May 2016, a paper was released detailing security vulnerabilities with the DAO that could allow Ether to be stolen.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] On 9 June 2016, Peter Vessenes publicly disclosed the existence of a critical security vulnerability overlooked in many Solidity contracts, a recursive call bug.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] On 12 June 2016, Stephan Tual publicly claimed that the DAO funds were safe despite the newly-discovered critical security flaw.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] On 15 July 2016, a short notice on-chain vote was held on the DAO hard fork.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] Of the 82,054,716 ETH in existence, only 4,542,416 voted, for a total voter turn out of 5.5% of the total supply on 16 July 2016; 3,964,516 ETH (87%) voted in favor, 1/4 of which came from a single address, and 577,899 ETH (13%) opposed the DAO fork.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] The expedited process of the carbon vote drew criticism from opponents of the DAO fork.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] Proponents of the fork were quick to market the vote as an effective consensus mechanism, pushing forward with the DAO fork four days later.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] The first Ethereum Classic block that was not included in the forked Ethereum chain was block number 1,920,000, which was generated by Ethereum Classic miners on 20 July 2016.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] A mechanism called the "Difficulty Bomb" was designed to push the Ethereum chain from proof-of-work consensus mechanism to proof-of-stake in the future by exponentially increasing the difficulty of mining.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] This Difficulty Bomb was added to the network on block 200,000 in an upgrade named "Ice Age".
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] While Ethereum Classic participants debated the merits of the Difficulty Bomb, a network upgrade called "Die Hard" at block 3,000,000 delayed the effects of the mechanism.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] Once the network participants came to consensus on the issue, Ethereum Classic upgraded its network on block 5,900,000 to permanently defuse the Difficulty Bomb.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] This abandoned a future with proof-of-stake and committed the network to the proof-of-work consensus mechanism.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] After the Ethereum Classic and Ethereum Foundation hardfork in 2016, multiple versions of the EVM existed.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] This led to the realization of the need for an interoperable EVM standard to connect multiple EVMs.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] In an attempt to modernize the Ethereum Classic EVM, several protocol upgrades were scheduled to activate features that the Ethereum network already enabled over the past years.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] Atlantis, activated in September 2019, enabled the Agharta upgrade, which included the outstanding Byzantium changes.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] Agharta was followed by the incorporation of the Constantinople patches through the January 2020 upgrade.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] Finally, with the Phoenix upgrade, Ethereum Classic achieved protocol parity with Ethereum, allowing for fully cross-compatible applications between the two networks.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] The Ethereum Classic development community continues to maintain protocol parity with the greater EVM standard.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] Development moves slowly, only updating stable versions of EVM standard.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] After a series of 51% attacks on the Ethereum Classic network in 2020, a change to the underlying Ethash mining algorithm was considered by the community to prevent being a minority proof-of-work chain in the Ethash mining algorithm where Ethereum is dominating the hashrate.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] After evaluating various options such as Monero's RandomX or the standardized SHA-3-256, it was eventually decided to double the Ethash epoch duration from 30,000 to 60,000 in order to reduce the DAG size and prevent Ethash miners to easily switch to Ethereum Classic.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] This modified Ethash is also referred to as *ETChash* or *Thanos* upgrade.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] Following Ethereum’s transition to a proof-of-stake consensus mechanism in 2022, Ethereum Classic achieved a notable milestone by becoming the largest and most secure proof-of-work blockchain supporting smart contract functionality.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] In 2025, the network's ETChash hashrate surpassed 300 terahashes per second (TH/s), a level not observed since Ethereum's DeFi summer boom cycle.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] Ethereum Classic subsequently established itself as the leading blockchain utilizing the Ethash algorithm family.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] This increase in computational power indicates greater participation by miners, broader network adoption, and enhanced network security.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] As with other cryptocurrencies, the validity of each ether is provided by a blockchain, which is a continuously growing list of records, called "blocks", which are linked and secured using cryptography.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] By design, the blockchain is inherently resistant to modification of the data.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] It is an open, distributed ledger that records transactions between two parties efficiently and in a verifiable and permanent way.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] Unlike bitcoin, Ethereum Classic operates using accounts and balances in a manner called state transitions.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] This does not rely upon unspent transaction outputs (UTXOs).
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] The state denotes the current balances of all accounts and extra data.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] The state is not stored on the blockchain, it is stored in a separate Merkle Patricia tree.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] A cryptocurrency wallet stores the public and private "keys" or "addresses" which can be used to receive or spend Ether.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] These can be generated through BIP 39 style mnemonics for a BIP 32 "HD wallet".
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] In the Ethereum tech stack, this is unnecessary as it does not operate in a UTXO scheme.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] With the private key, it is possible to write in the blockchain, effectively making an ether transaction.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] To send Ether to an account, the Keccak-256 hash of the public key of that account is needed.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] Ether accounts are pseudonymous in that they are not linked to individual persons, but rather to one or more specific addresses.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] It is listed under the currency code ETC and traded on cryptocurrency exchanges, and the Greek uppercase Xi character (Ξ) is generally used for its currency symbol.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] It is also used to pay for transaction fees and computational services on the Ethereum Classic network.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] Ethereum Classic addresses are composed of the prefix "0x", a common identifier for hexadecimal, concatenated with the rightmost 20 bytes of the Keccak-256 hash (big endian) of the ECDSA public key (the curve used is the so-called *secp256k1*, the same as bitcoin).
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] In hexadecimal, two digits represent a byte, meaning addresses contain 40 hexadecimal digits.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] Contract addresses are in the same format, however, they are determined by sender and creation transaction nonce.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] User accounts are indistinguishable from contract accounts given only an address for each and no blockchain data.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] Any valid Keccak-256 hash put into the described format is valid, even if it does not correspond to an account with a private key or a contract.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] This is unlike bitcoin, which uses base58check to ensure that addresses are properly typed.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] On 11 December 2017, the total supply of Ether on Ethereum Classic was hard capped at ETC 210,700,000 via the Gotham hard fork upgrade.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] This added a bitcoin-inspired deflationary emission schedule that is documented in Ethereum Classic Improvement Proposal (ECIP) 1017.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] The emission schedule, also known as "5M20", reduces the block reward by 20% every 5,000,000 blocks.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] The Ethereum Classic Improvement Proposal (ECIP) process enables engineers and computer scientists to propose modifications, upgrades, or fixes.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] Any software developer who is a GitHub user is allowed to make contributions to the ECIP process.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] There is a number of ECIP types, each listed in the table below.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] Supporters of Ethereum Classic argue that blockchain immutability is paramount, and that code should be treated as final ("code is law").
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] Opponents of this view, including the Ethereum Foundation, contended that recovering stolen DAO funds was justified to preserve user trust and that protocol governance must allow for exceptional intervention in extreme cases.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] The Ethereum community split over these philosophical differences, leading to the creation of two competing networks.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] Code is law refers to the idea that the code is above all else including law from outside forces such as a government.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] The law is written into the code, therefore, anything the code allows is legal.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] On 20 July 2016, due to reliance on the same clients, the DAO fork created a replay attack where a transaction was broadcast on both the ETC and ETH networks.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] On 13 January 2017, the Ethereum Classic network was updated to resolve transaction replay attacks.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] The networks are now officially operating separately.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] On 10 August 2016, the ETH proponent Robin Hood Group transferred 2.9 million stolen ETC to Poloniex in an attempt to sell ETC for ETH on the advice of Bitly SA; 14% was successfully converted to ETH and other currencies, 86% was frozen by Poloniex.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] On 30 August 2016, Poloniex returned the ETC funds to the RHG.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] They set up a refund contract on the ETC network.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] On 29 June 2017, the Ethereum Classic Twitter account made a public statement indicating reason to believe that the website for Classic Ether Wallet had been compromised.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] The Ethereum Classic Twitter account confirmed the details released via Threatpost.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] The Ethereum Classic team worked with Cloudflare to place a warning on the compromised domain warning users of the phishing attack.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] Ethereum Classic (ETC) has experienced two major 51% double-spending attacks in its history.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] These attacks exploit the decentralized nature of the network by gaining control of more than 50% of its mining power, allowing malicious actors to reorganize the blockchain, manipulate transactions, and double-spend digital assets.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] The first significant incident occurred in January 2019, when Ethereum Classic was targeted by a double-spending attack resulting in approximately US$1.1 million worth of ETC being fraudulently spent.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] The second major 51% attack took place in August 2020, on the fourth anniversary of the 2016 hard fork.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] This attack involved a series of deep chain reorganizations, leading to estimated losses of US$5.6 million and US$1.68 million from centralized exchanges, respectively.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] In response, the Ethereum Classic development community considered several network upgrades and ultimately adopted a modified version of the Ethash proof-of-work (PoW) consensus algorithm, known as ETChash.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] This change was implemented through the "ECIP-1099 Thanos Upgrade" in November 2020.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] The upgrade recalibrated the Directed Acyclic Graph (DAG) by reducing its size and slowing its growth rate by half, enabling 3GB Ethash mining hardware to continue securing the network.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] This adjustment also positioned Ethereum Classic to benefit from Ethash-compatible hardware rendered obsolete by blockchains adhering to the original DAG growth schedule.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] Following the Thanos Upgrade, Ethereum Classic's hashrate began a steady increase, eventually becoming the largest blockchain secured by the Ethash mining algorithm.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] In 2025, the ETChash network hashrate surpassed 300 terahashes per second (TH/s), a level not seen since Ethereum's "DeFi summer." As a result, Ethereum Classic solidified its position as the leading proof-of-work smart contract platform.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] In the immediate aftermath of the 2016 Ethereum hard fork, Ethereum Classic did not establish a formal foundation or central governing body.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] Instead, a small group of early contributors coordinated efforts to stabilise the network, maintain client software, support ecosystem development, and articulate the project's philosophical and technical direction.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] This group did not function as a formal governing authority but helped provide organisational coherence during a period when the network lacked established structures.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] One of the earliest areas of focus within Ethereum Classic, led by Avtar Sehra, was monetary policy.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] Early contributors advocated for clearer and more predictable issuance rules, in contrast to Ethereum's flexible monetary design at the time.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] These discussions contributed to community support for freezing the difficulty bomb — a mechanism originally embedded in Ethereum to incentivise protocol upgrades — through the Diehard hard fork in January 2017.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] In October 2016, **Avtar Sehra** authored **ECIP-1011**, one of the first major Ethereum Classic Improvement Proposal (ECIP).
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] The proposal introduced a decentralised chain identifier (chain ID) mechanism designed to prevent replay attacks between Ethereum and Ethereum Classic following the fork.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] The concept of chain identification introduced in ECIP-1011 was later adopted within Ethereum and became a standard component of chain identity across Ethereum-compatible networks.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] Ethereum Classic's early development relied primarily on volunteer contributors and community coordination rather than a centralised foundation.
[src:ethereum/ethereum-classic] This approach reflected the project's emphasis on immutability, decentralisation, and minimal governance intervention — principles that continue to influence its development philosophy.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Ethereum was conceived in 2013 by programmer Vitalik Buterin.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Other founders include Gavin Wood, Charles Hoskinson, Anthony Di Iorio, and Joseph Lubin.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] In 2014, development work began and was crowdfunded, and the network went live on 30 July 2015.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Ethereum allows anyone to deploy decentralized applications onto it, which anyone can then use.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Decentralized finance (DeFi) applications provide financial instruments that do not directly rely on financial intermediaries like brokerages, exchanges, or banks.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] This facilitates borrowing against cryptocurrency holdings or lending them out for interest.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Ethereum allows users to create fungible (e.g.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] ERC-20) and non-fungible tokens (NFTs) with a variety of properties, and to create smart contracts that can receive, hold and send those assets in accordance with the contract's immutable code and a transaction's input data.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] On 15 September 2022, Ethereum transitioned its consensus mechanism from proof-of-work (PoW) to proof-of-stake (PoS) in an update known as "The Merge", which cut the blockchain's energy usage by over 99%.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Ethereum was initially described in late 2013 in a white paper by Vitalik Buterin, a programmer and co-founder of *Bitcoin Magazine*, that described a way to build decentralized applications.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Buterin argued to the Bitcoin Core developers that blockchain technology could benefit from other applications besides money and that it needed a more robust language for application development that could lead to attaching real-world assets, such as stocks and property, to the blockchain.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] In 2013, Buterin briefly worked with eToro CEO Yoni Assia on the Colored Coins project and drafted its white paper outlining additional use cases for blockchain technology.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] However, after failing to gain agreement on how the project should proceed, he proposed the development of a new platform with a more robust scripting language—a Turing-complete programming language—that would eventually become Ethereum.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Ethereum was announced at the North American Bitcoin Conference in Miami, in January 2014.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] During the conference, Gavin Wood, Charles Hoskinson, and Anthony Di Iorio (who financed the project) rented a house in Miami with Buterin at which they could develop a fuller sense of what Ethereum might become.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Di Iorio invited friend Joseph Lubin, who invited reporter Morgen Peck, to bear witness.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Peck subsequently wrote about the experience in *Wired*.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Six months later the founders met again in Zug, Switzerland, where Buterin told the founders that the project would proceed as a non-profit.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Hoskinson left the project at that time and soon after founded IOHK, a blockchain company responsible for Cardano.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Ethereum has an unusually long list of founders.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Anthony Di Iorio wrote: "Ethereum was founded by Vitalik Buterin, Myself, Charles Hoskinson, Mihai Alisie & Amir Chetrit (the initial 5) in December 2013.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Joseph Lubin, Gavin Wood, & Jeffrey Wilcke were added in early 2014 as founders." Buterin chose the name Ethereum after browsing a list of elements from science fiction on Wikipedia.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Formal development of the software underlying Ethereum began in early 2014 through a Swiss company, Ethereum Switzerland GmbH (*EthSuisse*).The idea of putting executable smart contracts in the blockchain needed to be specified before it could be implemented in software.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] This work was done by Gavin Wood, then the chief technology officer, in the Ethereum Yellow Paper that specified the Ethereum Virtual Machine.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Subsequently, a Swiss non-profit foundation, the **Ethereum Foundation** (*Stiftung Ethereum*), was founded.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Development was funded by an online public crowd sale from July to August 2014, in which participants bought the Ethereum value token (ether) with another digital currency, bitcoin.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] While there was early praise for the technical innovations of Ethereum, questions were also raised about its security and scalability.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] The intended purpose of the three distinct implementations would be so that if one of them had a bug, the other two could be used as a comparison.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Several codenamed prototypes of Ethereum were developed over 18 months in 2014 and 2015 by the Ethereum Foundation as part of their proof-of-concept series.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] "Olympic" was the last prototype and public beta pre-release.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] The Olympic network gave users a bug bounty of 25,000 ether for stress-testing the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] On 30 July 2015, "Frontier" marked the official launch of the Ethereum platform, and Ethereum created its "genesis block".
[src:ethereum/ethereum] The genesis block contained 8,893 transactions allocating various amounts of ether to different addresses, and a block reward of 5 ETH.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Since the initial launch, Ethereum has undergone a number of planned protocol upgrades, which are important changes affecting the underlying functionality and/or incentive structures of the platform.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Protocol upgrades are accomplished by means of a hard fork.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] In 2016, a decentralized autonomous organization called The DAO—a set of smart contracts developed on the platform—raised a record US$150 million in a crowd sale to fund the project.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Emin Gün Sirer, Vlad Zamfir and Dino Mark had written a paper called *A Call for a Temporary Moratorium on The DAO* in which they described in which way the DAO might be vunerable to attacks.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] The DAO was exploited in June 2016 when US$50 million of DAO tokens were stolen by an unknown hacker.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] The event sparked a debate in the crypto-community about whether Ethereum should perform a contentious "hard fork" to reappropriate the affected funds.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] The fork resulted in the network splitting into two blockchains: Ethereum with the theft reversed, and Ethereum Classic which continued on the original chain.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] In March 2017, various blockchain startups, research groups, and *Fortune* 500 companies announced the creation of the Enterprise Ethereum Alliance (EEA) with 30 founding members.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] By May 2017, the nonprofit organization had 116 enterprise members, including ConsenSys, CME Group, Cornell University's research group, Toyota Research Institute, Samsung SDS, Microsoft, Intel, J.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Morgan, Cooley LLP, Merck KGaA, DTCC, Deloitte, Accenture, Banco Santander, BNY Mellon, ING, and National Bank of Canada.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] By July 2017, there were over 150 members in the alliance, including MasterCard, Cisco Systems, Sberbank, and Scotiabank.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] In 2024, Paul Brody, EEA board member for EY, was announced as the new chairperson, and Karen Scarbrough, board member for Microsoft, as the new executive director.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Vanessa Grellet from Arche Capital also joined as a new board member.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] In 2017, *CryptoKitties*, the blockchain game and decentralized application (dApp) featuring digital cat artwork as NFTs, was launched on the Ethereum network.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] In cultivating popularity with users and collectors, it gained notable mainstream media attention providing significant exposure to Ethereum in the process.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] It was considered the most popular smart contract in use on the network but it also highlighted concerns over Ethereum's scalability due to the game's substantial consumption of network capacity at the time.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] In January 2018, a community-driven paper (an EIP, "Ethereum Improvement Proposal") under the leadership of civic hacker and lead author William Entriken was published, called *ERC-721: Non-Fungible Token Standard.* It introduced ERC-721, the first official NFT standard on Ethereum.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] This standardization allowed Ethereum to become central to a multi-billion dollar digital collectibles market.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] By January 2018, ether was the second-largest cryptocurrency in terms of market capitalization, behind bitcoin.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] As of 2021, it maintained that relative position.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] In 2019, Ethereum Foundation employee Virgil Griffith was arrested by the US government for presenting at a blockchain conference in North Korea.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] He would later plead guilty to one count of conspiring to violate the International Emergency Economic Powers Act in 2021.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] In March 2021, Visa Inc. announced that it began settling stablecoin transactions using Ethereum.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] In April 2021, JP Morgan Chase, UBS, and MasterCard announced that they were investing US$65 million into ConsenSys, a software development firm that builds Ethereum-related infrastructure.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] There were two network upgrades in 2021.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] The first was "Berlin", implemented on 14 April 2021.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] The second was "London", which took effect on 5 August.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] The London upgrade included Ethereum Improvement Proposal ("EIP") 1559, a mechanism for reducing transaction fee volatility.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] The mechanism causes a portion of the ether paid in transaction fees for each block to be destroyed rather than given to the block proposer, reducing the inflation rate of ether and potentially resulting in periods of deflation.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] On 27 August 2021, the blockchain experienced a brief fork that was the result of clients running different incompatible software versions.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] "The Merge" (formerly called Ethereum 2.0) was a set of three updates (Bellatrix, Paris, and Shapella) that transitioned Ethereum's consensus protocol from proof-of-work to proof-of-stake.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Bellatrix updated the proof-of-stake Beacon chain and introduced economic slashing.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Paris was the event at block 15537393 on 15 September 2022 that merged Ethereum to the Beacon chain.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Shapella (Shanghai-Capella) was the update that allowed for staking withdrawals.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] The switch from proof-of-work to proof-of-stake has cut Ethereum's energy usage by over 99%.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] However, the effect this has on global energy consumption and climate change may be limited since the computers previously used for mining ether may be used to mine other cryptocurrencies that are energy-intensive.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] On 13 March 2024, "Dencun" or also "Deneb-Cancun" set of upgrades went live.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] These included EIP-4844 (Proto-Danksharding) which introduced "blobs" that can be used for general-purpose data-availability.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Because "Blob" data is stored only temporarily, it is much cheaper than using normal call data for storage.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] This allows for Ethereum Layer 2 (L2) networks to greatly reduce the cost of posting compressed transaction data to the Layer 1 (L1).
[src:ethereum/ethereum] The Prague-Electra ("Pectra") update was launched on 7 May 2025.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] The Fulu-Osaka update went live on 3 December 2025.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] This update introduced several protocol improvements.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Ethereum is a peer-to-peer network that maintains a database containing the storage values of all Ethereum accounts and processes state-altering transactions.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Approximately every 12 seconds, a batch of new transactions, known as a "block", is processed by the network.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Each block contains a cryptographic hash identifying the series of blocks that must precede it if the block is to be considered valid.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] This series of blocks is known as the blockchain.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Each "node" (network participant) connects with a relatively small subset of the network to offer blocks and unvalidated transactions (i.e. transactions not yet in the blockchain) to its peers for download, and it downloads any from its peers that it doesn't already have.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Each node usually has a unique set of peers, so that offering an item to its peers results in the propagation of that item throughout the entire network within seconds.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] A node's collection of unvalidated transactions is known as its "mempool".
[src:ethereum/ethereum] A node may choose to create a copy of the state for itself.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] It does this by starting with the genesis state and executing every transaction in the blockchain, in the proper order of blocks and in the order they are listed within each block.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Any Ethereum account may "stake" (deposit) 32 or more ETH to register a "validator".
[src:ethereum/ethereum] At the end of each "epoch" (32 block slots, each slot lasting 12 seconds), each validator is pseudorandomly assigned to one of the slots of the epoch after the next, either as the block proposer or as an attester.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] During a slot, the block proposer uses their mempool to create a block that is intended to become the new "head" (latest block) of the blockchain, and the attesters attest to which block is at the head of the chain.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] If a validator makes self-contradicting proposals or attestations, or if it is inactive, it loses a portion of its stake.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Any Ethereum account may send ETH to a validator at any time to increase its stake.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] A validator's attestation is given a weight equal to its stake or 2,048, whichever is less.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] According to the Ethereum protocol, the blockchain with the highest accumulated weight of attestations at any given time is to be regarded as the canonical chain.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Validators are rewarded for making valid proposals and attestations.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] A validator's rewards are paid via transactions within the same chain that contains their proposal or attestation, and therefore would have little or no market value unless that chain becomes the canonical chain.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] This incentivizes validators to support the chain that they think other validators view as the canonical chain, which results in a high degree of consensus.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Ether (ETH) is the cryptocurrency generated in accordance with the Ethereum protocol as a reward to validators in a proof-of-stake system for adding blocks to the blockchain.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Ether is represented in the state as an unsigned integer associated with each account, this being the account's ETH balance denominated in wei (1018 wei = 1 ether).
[src:ethereum/ethereum] At the end of each epoch, new ETH is generated by the addition of protocol-specified amounts to the balances of all validators that made valid block proposals or attestations in the epoch before the last (i.e. the epoch being finalized).
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Additionally, ether is the only currency accepted by the protocol as payment for the transaction fee.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] The transaction fee is composed of two parts: the base fee and the tip.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] The base fee is "burned" (deleted from existence) and the tip goes to the block proposer.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] The validator reward together with the tips provide the incentive to validators to keep the blockchain growing (i.e. to keep processing new transactions).
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Therefore, ETH is fundamental to the operation of the network.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Ether may be "sent" from one account to another via a transaction, the execution of which simply entails subtracting the *amount to be sent* from the sender's balance and adding the same amount to the recipient's balance.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Ether is often erroneously referred to as "Ethereum".
[src:ethereum/ethereum] The uppercase Greek letter Xi, Ξ, is sometimes used as a currency symbol for ether.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] There are two types of accounts on Ethereum: user accounts (also known as externally-owned accounts), and contract accounts.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Both types have an ETH balance, may transfer ETH to any account, may execute the code of another contract, or create a new contract, and are identified on the blockchain and in the state by an account address.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Contracts are the only type of account that has associated bytecode and storage (to store contract-specific state).
[src:ethereum/ethereum] The code of a contract is evaluated when a transaction is sent to it.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] The code of the contract may read user-specified data from the transaction, and may have a return value.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Ethereum account addresses are composed of the prefix "`0x`" (a common identifier for hexadecimal) concatenated with the rightmost 20 bytes of the Keccak-256 hash of the ECDSA public key (the curve used is the so-called *secp256k1*).
[src:ethereum/ethereum] In hexadecimal, two digits represent a byte, and so addresses contain 40 hexadecimal digits after the "`0x`", e.g.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] The Ethereum Virtual Machine (EVM) is the runtime environment for transaction execution in Ethereum.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] The EVM is a stack based virtual machine with an instruction set specifically designed for Ethereum.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] The instruction set includes, among other things, stack operations, memory operations, and operations to inspect the current execution context, such as remaining gas, information about the current block, and the current transaction.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] The EVM is designed to be deterministic on a wide variety of hardware and operating systems, so that given a pre-transaction state and a transaction, each node produces the same post-transaction state, thereby enabling network consensus.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] The formal definition of the EVM is specified in the Ethereum Yellow Paper.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] EVMs have been implemented in C++, C#, Go, Haskell, Java, JavaScript, Python, Ruby, Rust, Elixir, Erlang, and soon WebAssembly.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Gas is a unit of account within the EVM used in the calculation of the transaction fee, which is the amount of ETH a transaction's sender must pay to the network to have the transaction included in the blockchain.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Each type of operation which may be performed by the EVM is hardcoded with a certain gas cost, which is intended to be roughly proportional to the monetary value of the resources (e.g. computation and storage) a node must expend or dedicate to perform that operation.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] When a sender is creating a transaction, the sender must specify a *gas limit* and *gas price*.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] The *gas limit* is the maximum amount of gas the sender is willing to use in the transaction, and the *gas price* is the amount of ETH the sender wishes to pay to the network per unit of gas used.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] A transaction may only be included in the blockchain at a block slot that has a *base gas price* less than or equal to the transaction's *gas price*.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] The portion of the *gas price* that is in excess of the *base gas price* is known as the tip and goes to the block proposer; the higher the tip, the more incentive a block proposer has to include the transaction in their block, and thus the quicker the transaction will be included in the blockchain.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] The sender buys the full amount of gas (i.e. their ETH balance is debited *gas limit* × *gas price* and their gas balance is set to *gas limit*) up-front, at the start of the execution of the transaction, and is refunded at the end for any unused gas.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] If at any point the transaction does not have enough gas to perform the next operation, the transaction is reverted but the sender is still only refunded for the unused gas.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] In user interfaces, gas prices are typically denominated in gigawei (Gwei), a subunit of ETH equal to 10−9 ETH.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] The EVM's instruction set is Turing-complete.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Ethereum's smart contracts are written in high-level programming languages and then compiled down to EVM bytecode, which is then deployed to the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] They can be written in Solidity (a language library with similarities to C and JavaScript), as well as others.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Source code and compiler information are usually published on blockchain explorer websites soon after the launch of the contract so that users can see the code and verify that it compiles to the bytecode that is on-chain.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] One issue related to using smart contracts on a public blockchain is that bugs, including security holes, are visible to all but cannot be fixed quickly.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] One example of this is the 2016 attack on The DAO, which could not be quickly stopped or reversed.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] The ERC-20 (Ethereum Request-for-Comments #20) Token Standard allows for fungible tokens on the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] The standard, proposed by Fabian Vogelsteller in November 2015, implements an API for tokens within smart contracts.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] The standard provides functions that include the transfer of tokens from one account to another, getting the current token balance of an account, and getting the total supply of the token available on the network.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Smart contracts that correctly implement ERC-20 processes are called ERC-20 Token Contracts, and they keep track of created tokens on Ethereum.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Numerous cryptocurrencies have launched as ERC-20 tokens and have been distributed through initial coin offerings.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Ethereum also allows for the creation of unique and indivisible tokens, called non-fungible tokens (NFTs).
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Since tokens of this type are unique, they have been used to represent such things as collectibles, digital art, sports memorabilia, virtual real estate, and items within games.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] ERC-721 is the first official NFT standard for Ethereum and was followed up by ERC-1155 which introduced semi-fungibility; both are widely used, though some fully fungible tokens using ERC-20 have been used for NFTs such as *CryptoPunks*.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] The first NFT project, Etheria, a 3D map of tradable and customizable hexagonal tiles, was deployed to the network in October 2015 and demonstrated live at DEVCON1 in November of that year.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] In 2021, Christie's sold a digital image with an NFT by Beeple for US$69.3 million, making him the third-most-valuable living artist in terms of auction prices at the time, although observers have noted that both the buyer and seller had a vested interest in driving demand for the artist's work.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Decentralized finance (DeFi) offers financial instruments in a decentralized architecture, outside of companies' and governments' control, such as money market funds which let users earn interest.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] DeFi applications are typically accessed through a Web3-enabled browser extension or application, such as MetaMask, which allows users to directly interact with the Ethereum blockchain through a website.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Many of these DApps can connect and work together to create complex financial services.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Examples of DeFi platforms include MakerDAO.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Uniswap, a decentralized exchange for tokens on Ethereum grew from US$20 million in liquidity to US$2.9 billion in 2020.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] As of October 2020, over US$11 billion was invested in various DeFi protocols.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Additionally, through a process called "wrapping", certain DeFi protocols allow synthetic versions of various assets (such as bitcoin, gold, and oil) to be tradeable on Ethereum and also compatible with all of Ethereum's major wallets and applications.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Aave is a protocol for microlending using Ethereum.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Ethereum-based software and networks, independent from the public Ethereum chain, have been tested by enterprise software companies.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Interested parties have included Microsoft, IBM, JPMorgan Chase, Deloitte, R3, and Innovate UK (cross-border payments prototype).
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Barclays, UBS, Credit Suisse, Amazon, Visa, and other companies have also experimented with Ethereum.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] As of December 2025, the maximum theoretical throughput for Ethereum L1 is 238 TPS (given its current 60M gas limit, 12s blocks, and 21k gas cost for ETH transfers).
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Due to large smart contract and batch transaction using more gas in each block, the average transaction throughput is much less.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] As of January 2016, the Ethereum averaged about 25 transactions per second; this did not change after the move to proof-of-stake.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] In comparison, the Visa payment platform processes 45,000 payments per second.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] This has led some to question the scalability of Ethereum.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Ethereum's blockchain uses a Merkle–Patricia Tree to store account state in each block.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] The trie allows for storage savings, set membership proofs (called "Merkle proofs"), and light client synchronization.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] The network has faced congestion problems, such as in 2017 in relation to *CryptoKitties*.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Layer 2 (L2) is one of the approaches that the Ethereum ecosystem has developed in order to scale up and handle more transactions with lower transaction fees.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] A Layer 2 chain is a separate blockchain that extends Ethereum (Layer 1) and inherits the security guarantees of Ethereum.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] There are different types of L2 chains, including optimistic rollups and zero-knowledge rollups (zk rollups).
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Depending on their individual technical details, some L2 chains are capable of processing thousands of transactions per second.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] The legal status of ether (ETH), Ethereum's native token, remains subject to uncertainty and varies substantially from one jurisdiction to another.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] In the United States, regulatory authorities have increasingly signaled that ether should be treated as a commodity under the jurisdiction of the Commodity Futures Trading Commission (CFTC).
[src:ethereum/ethereum] The CFTC has repeatedly asserted its regulatory authority over Ethereum, with former CFTC Chairman Heath Tarbert stating in 2019 that "ETH is a commodity" and subsequent leadership maintaining this position.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] From a private law perspective, many jurisdictions have recognized ether as a form of intangible personal property that can be owned, transferred, and used as collateral, similar to other forms of personal property.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] In the United States specifically, the 2022 Amendments to the Uniform Commercial Code (UCC) introduced "controllable electronic records" (CERs) as a new category of personal property that includes digital assets like ether.
[src:ethereum/ethereum] Under UCC Article 12, ETH is classified as a CER, which provides a comprehensive framework for its commercial circulation.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Ethereum is a distributed network of computers (known as nodes) running software that can verify blocks and transaction data.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] The software must be run on your computer to turn it into an Ethereum node.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] There are two separate pieces of software (known as 'clients') required to form a node.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] You should understand the concept of a peer-to-peer network and the basics of the EVM before diving deeper and running your own instance of an Ethereum client.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Take a look at our introduction to Ethereum.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] If you're new to the topic of nodes, we recommend first checking out our user-friendly introduction on running an Ethereum node.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] A "node" is any instance of Ethereum client software that is connected to other computers also running Ethereum software, forming a network.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] A client is an implementation of Ethereum that verifies data against the protocol rules and keeps the network secure.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] A node has to run two clients: a consensus client and an execution client.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] These clients work together to keep track of the head of the Ethereum chain and allow users to interact with the Ethereum network.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] The modular design with multiple pieces of software working together is called encapsulated complexity (opens in a new tab).
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] This approach made it easier to execute The Merge seamlessly, makes client software easier to maintain and develop, and enables the reuse of individual clients, for example, in the layer 2 ecosystem.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] (Coupled execution and consensus clients) Simplified diagram of a coupled execution and consensus client.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Both execution clients and consensus clients exist in a variety of programming languages developed by different teams.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Multiple client implementations can make the network stronger by reducing its dependency on a single codebase.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] The ideal goal is to achieve diversity without any client dominating the network, thereby eliminating a potential single point of failure.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] The variety of languages also invites a broader developer community and allows them to create integrations in their preferred language.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] What these implementations have in common is they all follow a single specification.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Specifications dictate how the Ethereum network and blockchain functions.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Multiple trackers offer a real-time overview of nodes in the Ethereum network.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Note that due to the nature of decentralized networks, these crawlers can only provide a limited view of the network and might report different results.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] If you want to run your own node, you should understand that there are different types of node that consume data differently.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] In fact, clients can run three different types of nodes: light, full and archive.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] There are also options of different sync strategies which enable faster synchronization time.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Synchronization refers to how quickly it can get the most up-to-date information on Ethereum's state.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Full nodes do a block-by-block validation of the blockchain, including downloading and verifying the block body and state data for each block.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] There are different classes of full node - some start from the genesis block and verify every single block in the entire history of the blockchain.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Others start their verification at a more recent block that they trust to be valid (e.g., Geth's 'snap sync').
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Regardless of where the verification starts, full nodes only keep a local copy of relatively recent data (typically the most recent 128 blocks), allowing older data to be deleted to save disk space.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Older data can be regenerated when it is needed.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Archive nodes are full nodes that verify every block from genesis and never delete any of the downloaded data.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Syncing clients in any mode other than archive will result in pruned blockchain data.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] This means, there is no archive of all historical states but the full node is able to build them on demand.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Instead of downloading every block, light nodes only download block headers.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] These headers contain summary information about the contents of the blocks.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Any other information the light node requires gets requested from a full node.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] The light node can then independently verify the data they receive against the state roots in the block headers.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Light nodes enable users to participate in the Ethereum network without the powerful hardware or high bandwidth required to run full nodes.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Eventually, light nodes might run on mobile phones or embedded devices.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] The light nodes do not participate in consensus (i.e., they cannot be validators), but they can access the Ethereum blockchain with the same functionality and security guarantees as a full node.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Light clients are an area of active development for Ethereum and we expect to see new light clients for the consensus layer and execution layer soon.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] There are also potential routes to providing light client data over the gossip network (opens in a new tab).
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] This is advantageous because the gossip network could support a network of light nodes without requiring full nodes to serve requests.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Ethereum does not support a large population of light nodes yet, but light node support is an area expected to develop rapidly in the near future.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] In particular, clients like Nimbus (opens in a new tab), Helios (opens in a new tab), and LodeStar (opens in a new tab) are currently heavily focused on light nodes.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Running a node allows you to directly, trustlessly and privately use Ethereum while supporting the network by keeping it more robust and decentralized.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Running your own node enables you to use Ethereum in a private, self-sufficient and trustless manner.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] You don't need to trust the network because you can verify the data yourself with your client.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] "Don't trust, verify" is a popular blockchain mantra.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] A diverse set of nodes is important for Ethereum’s health, security and operational resiliency.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] If you run a full node, the whole Ethereum network benefits from it, even if you don't run a validator.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Interested in running your own Ethereum client?
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] For a beginner-friendly introduction visit our run a node page to learn more.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] If you're more of a technical user, dive into more details and options on how to spin up your own node.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Setting up your own node can cost you time and resources but you don’t always need to run your own instance.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] In this case, you can use a third party API provider.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] For an overview of using these services, check out nodes as a service.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] If somebody runs an Ethereum node with a public API in your community, you can point your wallets to a community node via Custom RPC and gain more privacy than with some random trusted third party.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] On the other hand, if you run a client, you can share it with your friends who might need it.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] The Ethereum community maintains multiple open-source execution clients (previously known as 'Eth1 clients', or just 'Ethereum clients'), developed by different teams using different programming languages.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] This makes the network stronger and more diverse.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] The ideal goal is to achieve diversity without any client dominating to reduce any single points of failure.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] This table summarizes the different clients.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] All of them pass client tests (opens in a new tab) and are actively maintained to stay updated with network upgrades.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] For more on supported networks, read up on Ethereum networks.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Each client has unique use cases and advantages, so you should choose one based on your own preferences.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Diversity allows implementations to be focused on different features and user audiences.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] You may want to choose a client based on features, support, programming language, or licences.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Hyperledger Besu is an enterprise-grade Ethereum client for public and permissioned networks.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] It runs all of the Ethereum Mainnet features, from tracing to GraphQL, has extensive monitoring and is supported by ConsenSys, both in open community channels and through commercial SLAs for enterprises.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] It is written in Java and is Apache 2.0 licensed.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Besu's extensive documentation (opens in a new tab) will guide you through all details on its features and setups.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Erigon, formerly known as Turbo‐Geth, started as a fork of Go Ethereum oriented toward speed and disk‐space efficiency.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Erigon is a completely re-architected implementation of Ethereum, currently written in Go but with implementations in other languages under development.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Erigon's goal is to provide a faster, more modular, and more optimized implementation of Ethereum.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] It can perform a full archive node sync using around 2TB of disk space, in under 3 days.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Go Ethereum (Geth for short) is one of the original implementations of the Ethereum protocol.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Currently, it is the most widespread client with the biggest user base and variety of tooling for users and developers.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] It is written in Go, fully open source and licensed under the GNU LGPL v3.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Learn more about Geth in its documentation (opens in a new tab).
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Nethermind is an Ethereum implementation created with the C# .NET tech stack, licensed with LGPL-3.0, running on all major platforms including ARM.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Nethermind also has detailed documentation (opens in a new tab), strong dev support, an online community and 24/7 support available for premium users.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Reth (short for Rust Ethereum) is an Ethereum full node implementation that is focused on being user-friendly, highly modular, fast and efficient.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Reth was originally built and driven forward by Paradigm, and is licensed under the Apache and MIT licenses.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Reth is production ready, and suitable for usage in mission-critical environments such as staking or high-uptime services.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Performs well in use cases where high performance with great margins is required such as RPC, MEV, indexing, simulations, and P2P activities.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Learn more by checking out the Reth Book (opens in a new tab), or the Reth GitHub repo (opens in a new tab).
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] These clients are still in earlier stages of development and are not yet recommended for production use.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] There are multiple consensus clients (previously known as 'Eth2' clients) to support the consensus upgrades.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] They are responsible for all consensus-related logic including the fork-choice algorithm, processing attestations and managing proof-of-stake rewards and penalties.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Lighthouse is a consensus client implementation written in Rust under the Apache-2.0 license.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] It is maintained by Sigma Prime and has been stable and production-ready since Beacon Chain genesis.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] It is relied upon by various enterprises, staking pools and individuals.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] It aims to be secure, performant and interoperable in a wide range of environments, from desktop PCs to sophisticated automated deployments.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Lodestar is a production-ready consensus client implementation written in Typescript under the LGPL-3.0 license.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] It is maintained by ChainSafe Systems and is the newest of the consensus clients for solo-stakers, developers and researchers.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Lodestar consists of a beacon node and validator client powered by JavaScript implementations of Ethereum protocols.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Lodestar aims to improve Ethereum usability with light clients, expand accessibility to a larger group of developers and further contribute to ecosystem diversity.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Nimbus is a consensus client implementation written in Nim under the Apache-2.0 license.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] It is a production-ready client in use by solo-stakers and staking pools.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Nimbus is designed for resource efficiency, making it easy to run on resource-restricted devices and enterprise infrastructure with equal ease, without compromising stability or reward performance.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] A lighter resource footprint means the client has a greater margin of safety when the network is under stress.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Prysm is a full-featured, open source consensus client written in Go under the GPL-3.0 license.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] It features an optional webapp UI and prioritizes user experience, documentation, and configurability for both stake-at-home and institutional users.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Visit Prysm docs (opens in a new tab) to learn more.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Teku is one of the original Beacon Chain genesis clients.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Alongside the usual goals (security, robustness, stability, usability, performance), Teku specifically aims to comply fully with all the various consensus client standards.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Teku offers very flexible deployment options.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] The beacon node and validator client can be run together as a single process, which is extremely convenient for solo stakers, or nodes can be run separately for sophisticated staking operations.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] In addition, Teku is fully interoperable with Web3Signer (opens in a new tab) for signing key security and slashing protection.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Teku is written in Java and is Apache 2.0 licensed.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] It is developed by the Protocols team at ConsenSys that is also responsible for Besu and Web3Signer.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Learn more in Teku docs (opens in a new tab).
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Grandine is a consensus client implementation, written in Rust under the GPL-3.0 license.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] It is maintained by the Grandine Core Team and is fast, high-performance and lightweight.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] It fits a wide range of stakers from solo stakers running on low-resource devices such as Raspberry Pi to large institutional stakers running tens of thousands of validators.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] To follow and verify current data in the network, the Ethereum client needs to sync with the latest network state.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] This is done by downloading data from peers, cryptographically verifying their integrity, and building a local blockchain database.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Synchronization modes represent different approaches to this process with various trade-offs.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Clients also vary in their implementation of sync algorithms.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Always refer to the official documentation of your chosen client for specifics on implementation.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] The execution layer may be run in different modes to suit different use cases, from re-executing the blockchain's world state to only syncing with the tip of the chain from a trusted checkpoint.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] A full sync downloads all blocks (including headers and block bodies) and regenerates the state of the blockchain incrementally by executing every block from genesis.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Archive nodes perform a full sync to build (and retain) a complete history of the state changes made by every transaction in every block.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Like a full sync, a fast sync downloads all blocks (including headers, transactions, and receipts).
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] However, instead of re-processing the historical transactions, a fast sync relies on the receipts until it reaches a recent head, when it switches to importing and processing blocks to provide a full node.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Snap syncs also verify the chain block-by-block.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] However, instead of starting at the genesis block, a snap sync starts at a more recent 'trusted' checkpoint that is known to be part of the true blockchain.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] The node saves periodic checkpoints while deleting data older than a certain age.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] These snapshots are used to regenerate state data as needed, rather than storing it forever.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Light client mode downloads all block headers, block data, and verifies some randomly.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Only syncs tip of the chain from the trusted checkpoint.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Optimistic sync is a post-merge synchronization strategy designed to be opt-in and backwards compatible, allowing execution nodes to sync via established methods.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] The execution engine can *optimistically* import beacon blocks without fully verifying them, find the latest head, and then start syncing the chain with the above methods.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Then, after the execution client has caught up, it will inform the consensus client of the validity of the transactions in the Beacon Chain.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] A checkpoint sync, also known as weak subjectivity sync, creates a superior user experience for syncing a Beacon Node.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] It's based on assumptions of weak subjectivity which enables syncing the Beacon Chain from a recent weak subjectivity checkpoint instead of genesis.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] Checkpoint syncs make the initial sync time significantly faster with similar trust assumptions as syncing from .
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] In practice, this means your node connects to a remote service to download recent finalized states and continues verifying data from that point.
[src:ethereum/nodes-and-clients] The third party providing the data is trusted and should be picked carefully.
[src:ethereum/transactions] Transactions are cryptographically signed instructions from accounts.
[src:ethereum/transactions] An account will initiate a transaction to update the state of the Ethereum network.
[src:ethereum/transactions] The simplest transaction is transferring ETH from one account to another.
[src:ethereum/transactions] To help you better understand this page, we recommend you first read Accounts and our introduction to Ethereum.
[src:ethereum/transactions] An Ethereum transaction refers to an action initiated by an externally-owned account, in other words an account managed by a human, not a contract.
[src:ethereum/transactions] For example, if Bob sends Alice 1 ETH, Bob's account must be debited and Alice's must be credited.
[src:ethereum/transactions] This state-changing action takes place within a transaction.
[src:ethereum/transactions] Transactions, which change the state of the EVM, need to be broadcast to the whole network.
[src:ethereum/transactions] Any node can broadcast a request for a transaction to be executed on the EVM; after this happens, a validator will execute the transaction and propagate the resulting state change to the rest of the network.
[src:ethereum/transactions] Transactions require a fee and must be included in a validated block.
[src:ethereum/transactions] To make this overview simpler we'll cover gas fees and validation elsewhere.
[src:ethereum/transactions] Gas is a reference to the computation required to process the transaction by a validator.
[src:ethereum/transactions] Users have to pay a fee for this computation.
[src:ethereum/transactions] The `gasLimit`, and `maxPriorityFeePerGas` determine the maximum transaction fee paid to the validator.
[src:ethereum/transactions] But a transaction object needs to be signed using the sender's private key.
[src:ethereum/transactions] This proves that the transaction could only have come from the sender and was not sent fraudulently.
[src:ethereum/transactions] An Ethereum client like Geth will handle this signing process.
[src:ethereum/transactions] With the signature hash, the transaction can be cryptographically proven that it came from the sender and submitted to the network.
[src:ethereum/transactions] The vast majority of transactions access a contract from an externally-owned account.
[src:ethereum/transactions] Most contracts are written in Solidity and interpret their data field in accordance with the .
[src:ethereum/transactions] The first four bytes specify which function to call, using the hash of the function's name and arguments.
[src:ethereum/transactions] You can sometimes identify the function from the selector using this database (opens in a new tab).
[src:ethereum/transactions] The rest of the calldata is the arguments, encoded as specified in the ABI specs (opens in a new tab).
[src:ethereum/transactions] For example, lets look at this transaction (opens in a new tab).
[src:ethereum/transactions] Use **Click to see More** to see the calldata.
[src:ethereum/transactions] There are several known functions with this signature (opens in a new tab).
[src:ethereum/transactions] In this case the contract source code (opens in a new tab) has been uploaded to Etherscan, so we know the function is `transfer(address,uint256)`.
[src:ethereum/transactions] According to the ABI specifications, integer values (such as addresses, which are 20-byte integers) appear in the ABI as 32-byte words, padded with zeros in the front.
[src:ethereum/transactions] Because the data field contains opaque hexadecimal bytes, it can be extremely difficult to verify what action a transaction will actually perform.
[src:ethereum/transactions] This "blind signing" vulnerability is addressed by **Clear Signing (opens in a new tab)** through the use of transaction descriptors (opens in a new tab) (defined by ERC-7730).
[src:ethereum/transactions] The ERC-7730 specification uses transaction descriptors (often structured as JSON files) to enrich the data found in ABIs and structured messages, like EVM transaction calldata, EIP-712 messages, and EIP-4337 User Operations.
[src:ethereum/transactions] Developers use these descriptors to map specific transaction variables directly into formatting templates, ensuring the underlying data remains machine-readable for applications.
[src:ethereum/transactions] On the frontend, wallets use this formatting context to translate opaque bytecode into clear, human-readable information.
[src:ethereum/transactions] As mentioned, transactions cost gas to execute.
[src:ethereum/transactions] Simple transfer transactions require 21000 units of Gas.
[src:ethereum/transactions] Any gas not used in a transaction is refunded to the user account.
[src:ethereum/transactions] Gas is required for any transaction that involves a smart contract.
[src:ethereum/transactions] Smart contracts can also contain functions known as `view` (opens in a new tab) or `pure` (opens in a new tab) functions, which do not alter the state of the contract.
[src:ethereum/transactions] As such, calling these functions from an EOA will not require any gas.
[src:ethereum/transactions] The underlying RPC call for this scenario is `eth_call`.
[src:ethereum/transactions] Unlike when accessed using `eth_call`, these `view` or `pure` functions are also commonly called internally (i.e., from the contract itself or from another contract) which does cost gas.
[src:ethereum/transactions] The transaction is then broadcasted to the network and added to a transaction pool consisting of all other pending network transactions.
[src:ethereum/transactions] A validator must pick your transaction and include it in a block in order to verify the transaction and consider it "successful".
[src:ethereum/transactions] As time passes the block containing your transaction will be upgraded to "justified" then "finalized".
[src:ethereum/transactions] These upgrades make it much more certain that your transaction was successful and will never be altered.
[src:ethereum/transactions] Once a block is "finalized" it could only ever be changed by a network level attack that would cost many billions of dollars.
[src:ethereum/transactions] Watch Austin walk you through transactions, gas, and mining.
[src:ethereum/transactions] Ethereum originally had one format for transactions.
[src:ethereum/transactions] Each transaction contained a nonce, gas price, gas limit, to address, value, data, v, r, and s.
[src:ethereum/transactions] Ethereum has evolved to support multiple types of transactions to allow for new features such as access lists and EIP-1559 (opens in a new tab) to be implemented without affecting legacy transaction formats.
[src:ethereum/transactions] EIP-2718 (opens in a new tab) is what allows for this behavior.
[src:ethereum/transactions] **Type 1 Transactions:** Introduced in EIP-2930 (opens in a new tab) as part of Ethereum's Berlin Upgrade, these transactions include an `accessList` parameter.
[src:ethereum/transactions] This list specifies addresses and storage keys the transaction expects to access, helping to potentially reduce gas costs for complex transactions involving smart contracts.
[src:ethereum/transactions] EIP-1559 fee market changes are not included in Type 1 transactions.
[src:ethereum/transactions] Type 1 transactions also include a `yParity` parameter, which can either be `0x0` or `0x1`, indicating the parity of the y-value of the secp256k1 signature.
[src:ethereum/transactions] They are identified by starting with the byte `0x01`, and their TransactionType value is `0x1`.
[src:ethereum/transactions] **Type 2 Transactions**, commonly referred to as EIP-1559 transactions, are transactions introduced in EIP-1559 (opens in a new tab), in Ethereum's London Upgrade.
[src:ethereum/transactions] They have become the standard transaction type on the Ethereum network.
[src:ethereum/transactions] These transactions introduce a new fee market mechanism that improves predictability by separating the transaction fee into a base fee and a priority fee.
[src:ethereum/transactions] They start with the byte `0x02` and include fields such as `maxPriorityFeePerGas` and `maxFeePerGas`.
[src:ethereum/transactions] Type 2 transactions are now the default due to their flexibility and efficiency, especially favored during periods of high network congestion for their ability to help users manage transaction fees more predictably.
[src:ethereum/transactions] The TransactionType value for these transactions is `0x2`.
[src:ethereum/transactions] **Type 3 (Blob) Transactions** were introduced in EIP-4844 (opens in a new tab) as part of Ethereum's Dencun Upgrade.
[src:ethereum/transactions] These transactions are designed to handle "blob" data (Binary Large Objects) more efficiently, particularly benefiting Layer 2 rollups by providing a way to post data to the Ethereum network at a lower cost.
[src:ethereum/transactions] Blob transactions include additional fields such as `blobVersionedHashes`, `maxFeePerBlobGas`, and `blobGasPrice`.
[src:ethereum/transactions] They start with the byte `0x03`, and their TransactionType value is `0x3`.
[src:ethereum/transactions] Blob transactions represent a significant improvement in Ethereum's data availability and scaling capabilities.
[src:ethereum/transactions] **Type 4 Transactions** were introduced in EIP-7702 (opens in a new tab) as part of Ethereum’s Pectra Upgrade.
[src:ethereum/transactions] These transactions are designed to be forward-compatible with account abstraction.
[src:ethereum/transactions] They allow EOAs to temporarily behave like smart contract accounts without compromising their original functionality.
[src:ethereum/transactions] They include an `authorization_list` parameter, which specifies the smart contract to which the EOA delegates its authority.
[src:ethereum/transactions] After the transaction, the EOA’s code field will have the address of the delegated smart contract.
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] Buterin was born in Kolomna, Russia, to a Russian family.
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] His father, Dmitry, was a computer scientist.
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] He and his parents lived in the area until he was the age of six, when his parents emigrated to Canada in search of better employment opportunities.
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] While in grade three of elementary school in Canada, Buterin was placed into a class for gifted children and was drawn to mathematics, programming, and economics.
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] Buterin then attended The Abelard School, a private high school in Toronto.
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] Buterin learned about Bitcoin from his father at the age of 17.
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] In 2012, Buterin won a bronze medal in the International Olympiad in Informatics in Italy.
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] After high school, Buterin attended the University of Waterloo.
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] There, he took advanced courses and was a research assistant for cryptographer Ian Goldberg, who co-created Off-the-Record Messaging and was the former board of directors' chairman of the Tor Project.
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] In 2013, he visited developers in other countries who shared his enthusiasm for code.
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] He returned to Toronto later that year and published a white paper proposing Ethereum.
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] He dropped out of university in 2014 when he was awarded with a grant of US$100,000 (equivalent to $135,999 in 2025) from the Thiel Fellowship, a scholarship created by venture capitalist Peter Thiel and went to work on Ethereum full-time.
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] On 30 November 2018, Buterin received an honorary doctorate from the Faculty of Business and Economics of the University of Basel.
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] In 2011, Buterin began writing for a publication called *Bitcoin Weekly* after meeting a person on a bitcoin forum with the aim of earning bitcoin.
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] The owner offered five bitcoin (about $3.50 at the time) to anyone who would write an article for him.
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] Buterin wrote for the site until it shut down soon thereafter due to insufficient revenue.
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] In September 2011, Mihai Alisie reached out to Buterin about starting a new print publication called *Bitcoin Magazine*, a position which Buterin would accept as the first co-founder and contribute to as a leading writer.
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] In addition, he was from 2016 to 2024 a member of the editorial board of *Ledger*, a peer-reviewed scholarly journal that publishes full-length original research articles on the subjects of cryptocurrency and blockchain technology.
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] Buterin is the inventor of Ethereum, described as a "decentralised mining network and software development platform rolled into one" that facilitates the creation of new cryptocurrencies and programs that share a single blockchain (a cryptographic transaction ledger).
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] Buterin first described Ethereum in a white paper in November 2013.
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] Buterin had argued that bitcoin needed a scripting language for application development.
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] But when he failed to gain agreement, he proposed development of a new platform with a more general scripting language.
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] The Ethereum white paper was circulated, and interest grew in the new protocol in late 2013 and early 2014.
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] Buterin announced Ethereum more publicly at the North American Bitcoin Conference in Miami on 26 January.
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] Buterin delivered a 25-minute speech, describing the general-purpose global computer operating on a decentralized permissionless network, ending with potential uses for Ethereum that ranged from crop insurance to decentralized exchanges to DAOs.
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] He's not too excited that the community assigns so much importance to him.
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] Buterin has stated that he was driven to create decentralized money because his World of Warcraft character was nerfed, specifically by patch 3.1.0.
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] Buterin has contributed as a developer to other open-source software projects.
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] He also contributed to DarkWallet by Cody Wilson, Bitcoin Python libraries, and the cryptocurrency marketplace site Egora.
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] As Buterin was recognizing the economic and political relevance of the Ethereum enterprise for his native Russia, he met with President Vladimir Putin on 2 June 2017, at the St.
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] Petersburg International Economic Forum (SPIEF).
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] Putin stated that he "supported the idea of establishing ties with possible Russian partners".
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] Buterin came into contact with economist Glen Weyl after tweeting about Weyl's proposal for a new wealth tax.
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] The two then wrote a manifesto *Liberation Through Radical Decentralization*, where they highlighted the common ground between Buterin's work on cryptocurrencies and Weyl's work on market-based solutions to social problems.
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] Collaborating with Zoe Hitzig, a PhD student at Harvard, they published a paper in 2019 entitled *A Flexible Design for Funding Public Goods*.
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] The paper sets out a method for optimal provision of public goods, using a version of quadratic voting.
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] As of August 2022, quadratic funding had been used to allocate over $20 million to open-source software projects, primarily through Gitcoin Grants.
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] In May 2021, Buterin donated $665 million to the Future of Life Institute, a nonprofit which, amongst other things, seeks to mitigate the existential risk from artificial intelligence.
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] Buterin worries that AI could become the new dominant species on Earth, and may "end humanity for good".
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] Buterin spoke out in support of Ukraine amid its invasion by Russia in 2022.
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] On the first day of the invasion, Buterin tweeted that "Ethereum is neutral, but I am not", and that the attack was a crime against both the Ukrainian and the Russian peoples.
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] A few days later, he responded to a tweet by RT's editor-in-chief Margarita Simonyan with "иди на хуй" 'go fuck yourself'.
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] She had claimed that people who said they were ashamed to be Russians because of Moscow's actions against Ukraine were, in fact, not Russians at all ("Если вам сейчас стыдно, что вы русские, не волнуйтесь, вы - не русские.").
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] Buterin has donated crypto to projects supporting the country and endorsed projects helping Ukraine through "cryptophilanthropy".
[src:ethereum/vitalik-buterin] These include Ukraine DAO, in which his father Dmitry is one of the key-holders on its multi-signature crypto safe.
